The Limit of Panic
Copenhagen – We often hear, we often know, how the world we know will come to an end, and usually the saying is ecological collapse.
In fact, the basic idea has been accompanying us since the Roman Club published its prophetic work "The Limits of Growth" over forty years ago.
But time is not forgiving.
"The Limits of Growth" warned humans in 1972 that a catastrophic collapse is near at hand.
However, we have since seen financial panic, but no real shortages or production collapses.
On the contrary, the resources created by human ingenuity have more than satisfied human consumption.
Yet the basic idea of "The Limits of Growth" still holds true: we continue a trend of being entangled in misleading solutions to minor issues, while ignoring the big problems and wise solutions.
By the early 1970s, the technological optimism had worn off, the Vietnam War had become a disaster, society was plunged into chaos, and the economy had stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" ignited public concern about pollution and sparked the modern environmental movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 book "The Population Bomb" made it clear that everything was at stake.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were filled with pessimism.
The intention of "The Limits to Growth" is to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people want to consume too many things.
Even if our geniuses give us some extra time, we will eventually destroy the Earth and ourselves with pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth itself, reduce consumption, practice recycling, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a significantly poorer level than today.
This perspective still resonates today, despite being completely wrong.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
However, even though commodity prices have recently rebounded, they have overall fallen to one-third of their level 150 years ago.
Technological innovation has replaced mercury in batteries, dental fillings, and thermometers, and by 2000, mercury consumption had decreased by 98% and prices had fallen by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, the supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more efficient new refining technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to be depleted in 1990 and 1992, respectively; today, reserves of both are higher than in 1970, despite a significant increase in our consumption.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves in the United States and reduced the price by half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per-capita GDP will increase 14-fold this century, with a 24-fold increase in developing countries.
The "Limits to Growth" was wrong because the authors ignored the greatest resource: our own intelligence.
Population growth has slowed since the 1960s.
Food supply has not collapsed (15 billion hectares of arable land are being utilized, and there are an additional 27 billion hectares in reserve).
Malnutrition rates have been halved, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not gotten the better of us.
The Roman Club imagined a picturesque past where we had no suspended particulate air pollution, were all happy farmers, and in the future, smokestacks would make it impossible for us to breathe. Reality is the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, and nearly 3 million people – equivalent to one in every 500 – died from air pollution each year, with most being indoor air pollution.
Today, this ratio has dropped to one death per 2000 people.
Although the number of deaths from pollution is still higher than that from malaria, its mortality rate is decreasing rather than increasing.
Despite this, the ideas fostered by "The Limits of Growth" still influence public and elite thinking.
Take recycling, for example. It is often just a feel-good gesture that comes at a great cost to the environment with minimal effect.
For instance, paper usually comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
What the programs and government subsidies for paper recycling brought was low-quality paper, protecting resources that were not under threat.
Similarly, policies worrying about overpopulation leading to self-destruction, such as China's one-child policy and India's forced sterilization, were implemented.
Furthermore, although pesticides and other pollutants were thought to kill half of humanity, good pesticide regulation resulted in only 20 deaths per year in the US, while pesticide use created more abundant and cheaper food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture – a movement stimulated by pesticide panic – would cost the US an additional $100 billion per year.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, and to maintain current output, 65 million hectares of land – half the area of modern California – would need to be farmed.
Price increases will lead to a decrease in the consumption of fruits and vegetables, resulting in severe negative health effects (including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer deaths per year).
Our obsession with dark scenarios prevents us from focusing on the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the largest killers, and yet, easily treatable diseases still claim 15 million deaths per year —— a quarter of the total deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people escape poverty, most can afford the cost of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past thirty years, China has lifted 680 million people out of poverty, leading the world in reducing the population living in poverty by nearly 1 billion people.
This has brought about a significant improvement in public health, life expectancy, and quality of life.
The forty years since the publication of "The Limits of Growth" have shown that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring in over $10 trillion per year by the end of this century, with benefits far exceeding the timid "feel-good" policies promoted by those who advocate fear.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and creating a brighter future with our limitless potential.
